Class Learned_DT

  • java.lang.Object
    • DT_Abstract1

  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class Learned_DT
extends DomainTheory
implements java.io.Serializable
    A Learned_DT is just a special kind of DomainTheory -- one that is learned, like a ConstextUnderConstruction. It holds records of test results for Leave-One-Out testing. With the academic phase completed, this class is used primarily in Learning Sessions to generate Suggestions. NOTE: It is not intended for use by Users, so messages are not translated.

      • learnKinTerm

        public void learnKinTerm(java.lang.String kinTerm,
                int maxNoise,
                int ignorable,
                int maxConf,
                DomainTheory sourceDT)
                  throws KSInternalErrorException,
                         KSParsingErrorException,
                         KSBadHornClauseException,
                         KSNoChainOfRelations2Alter,
                         KSConstraintInconsistency,
                         java.lang.ClassNotFoundException,
                         JavaSystemException,
                         java.io.FileNotFoundException,
                         java.io.IOException
        After loading Library resources, if necessary, we search the Library for kin term definitions from other known kinship systems whose pattern of kin types covered is a match or a superset of the kin types covered so far by the data for this kin term.

        If we find some candidate kin term definitions that are a solid match, then we prepare a recommendation for the User: - we propose the clearly best definition, if there is one, or - we suggest the additional data that would be most powerful in deciding among multiple candidates.

        If no solid candidates were found, then consider some 'noisy matches' -- definitions that would be a good fit if not for some misfit data. Based on a noisy match, we may ask User to re-examine the data that doesn't match the pattern; maybe it is noise (erroneous dyads).

        If both those methods fail, and the User has elected to try Sub-Pattern Matches, then try to piece together a definition from component clauses of Library partial matches.

        Finally, if all three methods fail, try to induce a definition by pure induction.

        In all cases, report any anomalies detected to User (but only ONCE) and always check for synonyms and umbrellas.
        Parameters:
        kinTerm - the kin term to be learned
        maxNoise - percent of misfit data that can be questioned as possibly erroneous. If more than this % don't match, they are assumed to represent a kinship fact of some kind.
        ignorable - percent of misfits data that can be ignored without correction
        maxConf - one half of the ignorable percent
        sourceDT - the domain theory that was cloned to make this learner
        Throws:
        KSInternalErrorException
        KSParsingErrorException
        KSBadHornClauseException
        KSNoChainOfRelations2Alter
        KSConstraintInconsistency
        java.lang.ClassNotFoundException
        JavaSystemException
        java.io.FileNotFoundException
        java.io.IOException
